His name is sometimes referred to as "Korkut" or sometimes as "Korkut Ata" in historical sources and various Oghuz narrations; It is also known as "Dede Korkut" in Western Turkish. While the folk narratives identified in the Sirderya basin introduced him as a baksi (Shaman), he was introduced as a Muslim Turkish guardian who served as a vizier and consultant to the rulers in written sources. In 2018, it was included in the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists of Turkey, Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan. He is also known as the pir of the Kazakh and Kyrgyz bahshis. According to a legend, he taught Kyrgyz shamans to play kopuz and sing folk songs.
